<HL>
   Israeli Consumer Prices Up
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<LP>
   JERUSALEM -- Israel's consumer price index rose 1.2% in
March, the government said.
   The price index measures price changes in a fixed
market-basket of goods and services. The state-run Central
Bureau of Statistics attributed the increase to price boosts
in all the items making up the basket, apart from clothes and
footwear.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   An increase of 2.2% was measured in housing costs, and it
followed a rise of 1.3% in February. Rents and home sale
prices have been pushed up because of a housing shortage
caused by an influx of Soviet Jews to Israel.
</TEXT>
