<HL>
   Lockheed Defeated
   Simmons Candidates,
   Official Tally Shows
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   LK NL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- Lockheed Corp.'s official tally of
voting at the March 29 annual meeting confirmed that
management soundly defeated dissident holder Harold Simmons'
board candidates. But management fell far short in its
attempt to defeat three Simmons-supported ballot measures.
   The annual meeting was briefly reconvened yesterday to
formally announce the ballot results. Afterward, Daniel
Tellep, Lockheed's chairman, and Vincent N. Marafino, vice
chairman and chief financial officer, had lunch with Mr.
Simmons and his top strategist, J. Landis Martin.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Simmons presented Mr. Tellep with a five-page letter
outlining the stockholder's recommendations for the company.
The letter apparently covered most of the issues raised in
the proxy battle.
   Lockheed declined to discuss the meeting and the letter.
   The ballot results, preliminary indications of which were
given by Lockheed a week ago, mark the end of a bitter proxy
fight. Mr. Simmons, a Dallas investor who controls 18.9% of
the nation's sixth-largest defense contractor, has said his
forces spent considerably more than $6 million pushing their
slate. Lockheed spent about $8 million.
   Lockheed said that of the 52.7 million shares voted,
incumbent Lockheed directors received between 57.6% and
60.7%; nominees of Mr. Simmons' Houston-based NL Industries
Inc. got 36.9%.
   However, three measures to increase shareholder rights,
one of which was proposed by NL Industries and the other two
supported by it, were approved with favorable votes of 54% to
61%.
   A Lockheed bylaw amendment to exempt the company from
antitakeover provisions of the Delaware corporate law won on
a 61% to 37% vote, with 2% abstaining. A recommendation for
Lockheed to adopt confidential voting procedures won 60% to
38%. And NL Industries' proposal that Lockheed redeem its
shareholder-rights plan passed 54% to 41%.
   Mr. Tellep didn't comment on the approval of the three
measures management had opposed, but he said "the decided
margin of victory for the incumbent board of directors gives
us a clear mandate to go forward" with current corporate
plans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900417-0135
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900417-0135.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor --
   North Korea:
   Handle With Care
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A23
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   Your March 12 editorial "What's Up, Kim?" correctly
asserted that the discovery by South Korea of yet another
North Korean invasion tunnel under the Demilitarized Zone
symbolizes the threatening nature of the dictatorship in
Pyongyang and its "communist absolutism." However, it failed
to mention that, despite continuing high tensions on the
peninsula, some U.S. politicians and opinion makers are
calling for significant cuts or even complete withdrawal of
the 43,000-strong American troop presence in South Korea. The
U.S. should take care to prevent the euphoria over improved
East-West relations from distorting its perception of Korea.
   Pyongyang maintains a feverish military buildup and has
about a million soldiers, one of the world's largest armies.
The combined force strength of the U.S. and South Korea, on
the other hand, is about 700,000. The North deploys about 65%
of its military strength in forward areas near its border
with the South. In short, a strong first-strike capability
remains a high North Korean priority.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite new and flexible diplomatic initiatives recently
advanced by Seoul and Washington, Pyongyang has refused to
allow progress toward achieving even basic
confidence-building measures such as South-North summit
meetings and trade ties. The North remains uncommitted to
good-faith negotiations and appears to approach inter-Korean
relations with one outcome in mind: the eventual domination
of the entire peninsula under the North's rule.
   Since the end of the Korean War, the deterrence
represented by America's strong political and military
commitment to South Korea has worked. The litmus test for the
U.S. should be a simple one: When the threat from the North
has diminished sufficiently, it will be time to begin
removing American troops from Korea. This approach not only
sustains adequate deterrence but also allows South Korea to
bargain with Pyongyang from a position of strength. Recent
U.S. experience in dealing with the Soviet Union gives
credence to this course of action.
   DARYL M. PLUNK
   Visiting Fellow
   Asian Studies Center
   Heritage Foundation
   Washington
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900417-0134
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900417-0134.
</DOCID>
