<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. capital markets, with terms and syndicate
manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets Report:
                                                                                                       

                      MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   King County, Wash. -- the bulk of $130 million of
unlimited tax general obligation bonds, 1990 Series A, and
limited tax general obligation bonds, 1990 Series B, due Dec.
1, 1992-2009, apparently was won by a First Boston Corp.
group with a bid setting the true interest cost at 7.05%. The
First Boston group apparently won the $117.6 million of
unlimited tax general obligation bonds, 1990 Series A. The
Series A bonds, rated double-A-1 by Moody's Investors Service
Inc. and double-A-plus by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., were
priced for reoffering to yield from 6.10% in 1992 to 7.15% in
2008 and 2009. There are no term bonds. Details on the winner
of the remainder of the issue, the Series B limited tax
general obligation bonds, weren't readily available.
   Connecticut -- $75 million of general obligation capital
appreciation bonds, College Savings Plan, 1990 Series A, due
May 15, 1995-2010, were tentatively priced by a Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. group to yield to maturity from 6.40% in
1995 to 7.15% in 2009 and 2010. There are no term bonds. The
bonds are rated double-A by Moody's and S&amp;P and will be sold
to retail investors only.
                                                                                                       

                       MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Perpetual Savings Bank -- about $200 million of mortgage
pass-through certificates was underwritten by Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. and Salomon Brothers Inc. The certificates
represent undivided interests in a pool of one-year,
Treasury-indexed, adjustable-rate residential mortgages
originated or purchased by Perpetual. The issue was rated
double-A-2 by Moody's, Perpetual said. Credit enhancement
consists primarily of a pool insurance policy issued by
General Electric Mortgage Insurance Co. The pool of mortgage
loans has an initial aggregate principal balance of about
$200 million and a remaining term to maturity of about 345
months. Interest will be passed through to the certificate
holders monthly at a rate equal to the weighted average
mortgage note rate less servicing and administrative fees.
The initial pass-through rate is about 8.46%. Perpetual will
be master servicer.
                                                                                                       

                        OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Federal Farm Credit Banks -- $250 million of notes, due
May 1, 1992, were priced at par for variable price reoffer.
The non-callable notes were priced at a spread of 0.34
percentage point above the Treasury's three-month bill
through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Student Loan Marketing Association -- $250 million of
notes, due April 24, 1991, was priced at par for variable
price reoffer. The non-callable notes were priced at a spread
of 0.225 percentage point above the Treasury's three-month
bill.
