<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   The Ordinary People's Story
   ----
   By Jonathan Kandell
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<LP>
   Few cities have transformed themselves as dramatically as
Tokyo in the past century. It was only in 1867 under the
Meiji emperor that the city abandoned feudalism and opened
itself to an overwhelmingly stronger Western world. What
happened next has been told in numerous tomes that usually
focus on leading politicians, military officers and
industrialists.
   The merit of Edward Seidensticker's approach is that he
rummages through the basement of history, attempting to
decipher how ordinary residents of Tokyo lived through
momentous changes. An earlier book, "Low City, High City,"
covered the period until 1923. In this sequel, "Tokyo Rising"
(Knopf, 362 pages, $24.95), the author, one of our foremost
translators of Japanese literature, updates the story to
current times.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Seidensticker has a talent for pithy observation. For
those in search of unchanging Japan, he advises a poorer
Tokyo neighborhood rather than a rich one: "Shabbiness does
not change, while the world of the rich and powerful seems to
change by the minute." One often hears that as a city grows
in wealth and importance, it becomes a more alienating place.
Mr. Seidensticker lifts the notion above cliche when he
remarks: "Almost all writers live in Tokyo today, and none
write of it as if it were home."
   But for the most part, his technique might be called
lunging for the capillaries. It can be effective when, for
example, he explains how the great earthquake of 1923 brought
about a Westernization of dress codes in Tokyo. Before the
disaster, department stores required shoppers to follow the
traditional practice of removing their shoes and donning
slippers. Customers good-naturedly accepted the inevitable
mixups when they tried to retrieve their footwear after
making their purchases.
   The specter of another earthquake causing people to flee
barefoot from the premises, or, still worse, to clog up the
exits while searching for their shoes, led to a typically
Japanese solution that balanced old and new ways: People
continued to remove their shoes before entering homes, but
kept them on while shopping.
   This sort of microcosmic approach works less well when Mr.
Seidensticker deals with the years leading to World War II.
He conveys little of the trauma, intolerance and xenophobia
of that era. We are told that popular singers who had taken
Western nicknames reverted to their Japanese names. Baseball,
we learn, was forced to pretend it was invented in Japan, and
American terms such as "play ball," "strike" and "pitcher,"
were replaced by Japanese words.
   More fundamentally, the reader is left to wonder what was
going through the minds of Tokyo residents when their
government vaunted the racial supremacy of the Japanese,
arrested anybody remotely considered a dissident, and sent
millions of citizens to kill and die overseas for the Greater
Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere.
   "There were many ways, chief among them, perhaps,
geographic isolation, to account for the fact that Japan had
no organized resistance and no selfless underground martyrs,"
notes Mr. Seidensticker. "In any event, it had none." Subject
closed. It's difficult to imagine accounts of Germany and
Italy giving such short shrift to the 1930s.
   With the horrific U.S. firebombing of Tokyo during World
War II, the book takes on the immediacy of journalism. Whole
neighborhoods are incinerated and parks are converted into
cemeteries. Four million people flee Tokyo. Among the three
million who stay behind, as many as 300,000 are homeless. At
the zoo, the carnivores and larger animals are put to death
because the government fears the bombings might free them
from their cages to roam wild in the streets.
   This account of wartime devastation gives the book a new
momentum that continues through the remaining pages.
Insightful anecdotes and elegant prose enhance rather than
replace narrative.
   Evoking the food shortages of the early postwar era, Mr.
Seidensticker writes: "In those days when the almost
universal way of transporting babies was by strapping them to
adult backs, a woman would seek to disguise her black-market
rice by strapping it. . . . and making soothing noises to it,
quite as if it were a baby. This woman's sack had sprung a
leak and rice was trickling out." A policeman, reluctant to
arrest the poor offender, taps her on the shoulder and says,
"Your baby is wetting its pants."
   Barely two decades later, Japan had emerged as an economic
superpower. People had become affluent so quickly that in a
1967 poll, 90% of Tokyo housewives listed themselves as
middle class -- up from 50% only three years before. Their
husbands' expense accounts have grown large enough to turn
Tokyo into the entertainment capital of the world. In some
districts, bars and restaurants outnumber residents.
   The Japanese, so fearful of Western superiority only a
century before, now wonder whether they have anything at all
to learn from the rest of the world. Mr. Seidensticker
suggests they might start by endowing their overbuilt,
unaesthetic capital with qualities befitting its new global
status. Citing the grandeur of New York when the U.S. was the
moneyed country of the world, and the harmony of Amsterdam,
Paris and London during their nations' periods of splendor,
he doubts whether Tokyo is headed for either grandeur or
harmony.
   ---
   Mr. Kandell, a former resident of Tokyo, is an assistant
foreign editor of the Journal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900417-0088
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900417-0088.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dataproducts Agrees to Be Acquired
   By Hitachi Venture for $160 Million
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   DPC J.HTK J.NIE HIT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. -- Dataproducts Corp. said it
signed a definitive agreement to be acquired for $160 million
by a joint venture formed by two affiliates of Hitachi Ltd.,
the Tokyo electronic equipment maker.
   The affiliates, Hitachi Koki Co. and Nissei Sangyo Co.,
said they will launch a $10-a-share tender offer within five
days for all of Dataproducts' stock outstanding. The offer
will be followed by a merger in which any remaining shares
will be acquired at the same price.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In American Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Dataproducts jumped $3.25 to $9.625 on volume of more than
1.5 million shares.
   The agreement appears to end two years of turmoil during
which time Dataproducts fended off a hostile suitor, sought
"strategic" bidders to buy the company, sold its headquarters
building and Southern California manufacturing operations,
and used those proceeds to repurchase 20% of its stock.
   The proposed merger gives Dataproducts the "strategic
partner" it has been searching for. Jack C. Davis, chairman
and chief executive officer, said he expects to remain in
those posts and that no immediate changes in company programs
are expected. Mr. Davis said he anticipates that he will be
joined on the board by representatives of Hitachi Koki and
Nissei Sangyo.
   "There's good chemistry here; we have similar kinds of
motivations for long-term investments and a belief in
focusing on quality products," Mr. Davis said. "As time goes
along, we'll be looking for ways to gain" from the new
ownership.
   Mr. Davis said that Dataproducts, a computer printer maker
with 1989 sales of $353 million, is strong in the U.S. and
Canada. Nissei Sangyo, Hitachi's 56.9%-owned trading arm, had
world-wide sales of 482 billion ($3.05 billion) yen last
year. "They have strengths in many, many countries we don't
have a presence in," Mr. Davis said.
   Hitachi Koki, 22.5% owned by Hitachi, had sales of 109
billion yen last year and makes power tools, printers and
scientific instruments. In the printer business, "we compete
with Hitachi Koki at the top of our line and bottom of their
line," Mr. Davis said.
   DPC Acquisition Corp., which was forced to terminate a
$10-a-share tender offer for Dataproducts in January because
it couldn't obtain financing, expressed disappointment in the
merger agreement. The New York investment group, which holds
about one million Dataproducts shares, is controlled by
Crescott Investment Associates, Wilson Investment Group,
Kernel Corp. and Catalyst Partners.
   "Management should have been able to obtain a better
price. A strategic buyer can pay more for a company's assets
than a financial buyer," said Micki Hidayatallah, Crescott's
chief executive officer. He said it wasn't clear whether DPC
would or could take any action, in light of a standstill
agreement with Dataproducts.
   Dataproducts's board believes that the merger agreement
"is in the best interests of shareholders, as well as our
employees, customers and suppliers," Mr. Davis said. The bid
is fully financed, whereas "DPC was never able to raise any
financing or a `highly confident' letter," he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900417-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900417-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Manufacturers
   Hanover, Chase
   Post Lower Net
   ---
   Operations at J.P. Morgan
   Anemic in 1st Quarter;
   New Unit Aids Banc One
   ----
   By Robert Guenther
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MHC CMB JPM ONE
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Four major banks reported generally weak earnings,
reflecting varying factors, including lower borrowing levels
for corporate takeovers, mounting bad loans and the absence
of interest payments from Brazil.
   Chase Manhattan Corp., the parent of the nation's
second-largest bank, posted the biggest earnings drop
yesterday -- a decline of 67% -- chiefly because of a $75
million increase in the provision for possible credit losses
on commercial real estate loans.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   An accounting change at J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. more than
doubled quarterly profit, masking continued anemic operating
earnings. Without the change, profit would have been off 6%.
   At Manufacturers Hanover Corp., a big drop in loan
syndication fees depressed earnings 7% from the year-earlier
level.
   And Banc One Corp.'s 17% rise resulted partly from its
acquisitions of two Texas banks. Excluding the Texas
acquisitions and certain one-time items, after-tax profit was
up 4.7%.
   All common stock prices except Banc One's sagged yesterday
in New York Stock Exchange composite trading on the earnings
news. Chase fell $1.625 a share to close at $27.75; Morgan
declined 75 cents to close at $34.75; and Manufacturers'
stock fell 62.5 cents to close at $33.875. Banc One stock
edged up 12.5 cents to close at $29.125 a share.
                                                                                                       

   Chase Manhattan
                                                                                                       

   Today's tougher regulatory environment for banks was
reflected in Chase's decision to increase its provision for
possible loan losses to $225 million, compared with $130
million in last year's fourth quarter.
   James J. McDermott, research director at Keefe, Bruyette &amp;
Woods Inc., said: "Here we see the handiwork of the
regulatory examination process. Banks are anticipating
rigorous examinations and are adding to their provisions."
   In a statement, Chase said that future provisions will
continue at high levels if the domestic commercial real
estate market deteriorates further.
   Despite the higher provision, Chase's nonperforming assets
remained below the levels of a year earlier on both a
relative and absolute basis. Total nonaccruing loans stood at
$4.19 billion, or 3.82% of total assets, compared with $4.2
billion, or 4.08%, a year earlier.
   Net charge-offs of bad loans for the quarter totaled $325
million, more than double the $159 million charged in the
same period a year earlier. Commercial real estate
charge-offs were $15 million, up from only $1 million a year
earlier. Charge-offs of domestic consumer loans rose by $23
million, to $83 million, largely because of portfolio growth.
   Net interest income totaled $814 million for the quarter,
down 1.8% from $829 million a year earlier. The 1989 interest
figure includes $61 million in Brazilian payments, compared
with none in the latest quarter. Non-interest income for the
period rose 11.4% to $468 million, as consumer banking fees,
trust fees and securities trading posted gains from last
year's period.
                                                                                                       

   J.P. Morgan
                                                                                                       

   While Morgan showed none of the loan-quality problems
bedeviling other banks, it is feeling the slowing pace of the
general economy and corporate finance activity.
   Excluding the effect of an accounting change for contracts
hedging interest-rate, currency and commodity risks, Morgan's
first-quarter results showed a drop in earnings to $169
million from $180 million a year earlier. Part of that
decline reflects last year's receipt of $27 million in
Brazilian interest payments; the latest quarter included no
Brazilian payments.
   Morgan's "asset quality remains impeccable," said Mr.
McDermott of Keefe Bruyette. "For them, revenue generation is
a key issue, and expenses continue to be high."
   Net interest income fell 11% to $266 million from $299
million, as Brazil's de facto debt moratorium and tighter
margins squeezed Morgan's net yield on interestearning assets
to 1.43% from 1.63% a year earlier.
   More than making up for that reduction were strong
foreign-exchange and securities-trading results, which both
more than doubled to $73 million and $140 million
respectively. The strong gains in part reflected the U.S.
dollar's rise during the first quarter.
   But one of Morgan's mainstays -- fees from advising
corporations on financial matters -- was hurt during the
period by ebbing takeover activity. Those fees fell 30% to
$62 million in the latest period.
   Operating expenses climbed 11% from a year earlier, but
dropped 9% from the fourth quarter, when costs related to its
move to new headquarters were especially high.
                                                                                                       

   Manufacturers Hanover
                                                                                                       

   Two factors -- sharply lower fees from arranging loans for
leveraged buy-outs of corporations and the lack of interest
payments by Brazil and Argentina -- detracted from an
otherwise improving picture at Manufacturers.
   Chairman John F. McGillicuddy said, "Although earnings
were down, they were nevertheless achieved in a difficult
environment, including a slowdown in corporate finance
activities."
   Manufacturers is one the leading arrangers of senior bank
debt for leveraged buy-outs, and the slowdown in that
activity has hurt the bank's results. The latest quarter
included only $11 million in loan syndication fees, down 70%
from $37 million a year ago.
   Similarly, the absence of interest payments by certain
Latin American borrowers reduced interest income by $18
million.
   Despite those factors, Manufacturers was able to post
gains in both the interest and non-interest categories of
income. Net interest income was $378 million, up slightly
from $373 million a year earlier. And non-interest revenue
also rose a bit, to $326 million from $319 million.
   Reflecting improved credit quality, Manufacturers' total
nonperforming assets and net charge-offs, excluding those of
loans to developing countries, dropped during the period.
                                                                                                       

   Banc One
                                                                                                       

   The Columbus, Ohio, bank holding company attributed its
record results to the inclusion of $10.7 million in its net
income by the newly created Bank One unit of Texas. That unit
is made up of the former Deposit Insurance Bridge Bank of
Dallas, whose results were included for the full quarter, as
well as Bright Bank Savings Association of Dallas, whose
results were included from Feb. 2.
   As of March 31, Banc One said its nonperforming assets
were 1.5% of total loans, or $277 million, an increase of 7%
over its year-end total of $259 million.
   Banc One noted that its assets excluding Bank One of Texas
were $27.2 billion at the quarter's end. The Texas unit had
assets of $14 billion, including $2.4 billion attributable to
certain provisions stemming from its purchase of the once
troubled Texas lenders.
   ---
   Thomas F. O'Boyle contributed to this article.
   ---
                                                                                                       

                         1990             1989
                     in      per         in      per     %
                  millions  share     millions  share   chg.
                                                                                                       

                  FIRST QUARTER NET INCOME
                                                                                                       


