<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   NBC Remains No. 1 for Prime Time
   During Latest Season; CBS Is Third
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B10
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB GE CBS NWS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- For the fifth consecutive year, NBC finished
as the No. 1 rated network in prime time, although its
audience was down 9% from last year and "The Cosby Show," the
cornerstone of its success, was no longer the top-ranked
program.
   In figures expected to be released today, National
Broadcasting Co., a unit of General Electric Co., was rated
No. 1 for the 30-week 1989-90 season with a 14.6 rating,
followed by Capital Cities/ABC Inc.'s network with a 12.9
rating. CBS Inc.'s TV network was third for the third
consecutive year with a 12.2 rating. A rating point equals
921,000 households with televisions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Last year, NBC finished first with a rating of 16, ABC was
second with 12.9 and CBS was last with 12.2.
   Overall, the three major networks attracted 65% of the
available audience, down 2% from last year. The networks
continue to lose viewers to alternatives such as cable
networks and News Corp.'s Fox Broadcasting Co., which has
only eight hours of prime-time programming weekly and isn't a
full-scale network.
   ABC, which enjoyed prime-time supremacy in the late
1970's, showed significant improvement against NBC in the
1989-90 season, which ended Sunday. For instance, "Roseanne"
was the top-rated show, unseating "The Cosby Show," albeit by
two-tenths of a rating point.
   ABC also posted crucial gains in two difficult time
periods: Sundays at 8 p.m., with "America's Funniest Home
Videos," which began in January and landed in fourth place,
and Thursdays at 9 p.m., with its new dramatic series "Twin
Peaks." Last week, in the first broadcast as a one-hour
series, "Twin Peaks" gave ABC its best ratings in that time
period in four years. It is up against NBC's popular "Cheers"
in the first half-hour.
   Network executives conceded yesterday that of the 23
series introduced last September, virtually none were
considered a hit, although ABC said it is pleased with
"Doogie Howser, M.D.," a half-hour show about a teen-age
doctor. Each network had its own disappointment: CBS bombed
with its highly touted "Famous Teddy Z," about a mailroom
clerk-turned-Hollywood talent agent; NBC lost with "Nutt
House," created by movie screenwriter and director Mel
Brooks, and ABC failed with comedian Jackie Mason's "Chicken
Soup."
   CBS made inroads in the critical 8 p.m. time period on
Mondays with the half-hour comedy "Major Dad" and on Tuesdays
with the one-hour reality-based series "Rescue: 911."
   As previously reported, NBC saw an erosion of 13% in every
key demographic group that advertisers want to attract,
including the highly sought-after group of women from 18 to
49 years old. In comparison, CBS's viewing groups were down
an average of 7% and ABC was flat from year to year.
   "We feel comfortable that we're poised for next year,"
said Alan Wurtzel, ABC's senior vice president of research.
In a news conference last week, ABC Entertainment President
Robert A. Iger declined to speculate on whether ABC would
overtake NBC next season. ABC hasn't been No. 1 since the
1979-80 season when it tied with CBS.
   "The lesson this year," said Bob Niles, vice president of
research at NBC, "was dare to be different."
   Such a philosophy led to success with ABC's "America's
Funniest Home Videos" and so far with "Twin Peaks" and with
Fox's "The Simpsons."
   Mr. Niles said some series introduced by NBC late in the
season, including "Carol &amp; Company" starring Carol Burnett,
show promise. In its first outing in its regular Saturday 10
p.m. time slot, the show won its time period.
   ---
                   Top Prime-Time Shows
                                                                                                       

                    For 1989-90 Season
                                                                                                       

     SHOW                             NETWORK       RATING
                                                                                                       

   1 "Roseanne" .....................  ABC           23.3
   2 "The Cosby Show" ...............  NBC           23.1
   3 "Cheers" .......................  NBC           22.9
   4 "America's Funniest Home Videos"  ABC           21.2
   5 "A Different World".............  NBC           21.1
                                                                                                       

   NOTE: A ratings point equals 921,000 homes with television
</TEXT>
