<HL>
   World Bank Approves
   Loan of $400 Million
   To Aid Yugoslavia
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The World Bank approved a $400 million loan
to Yugoslavia to help the country adopt market-related
reforms and expand imports, bank officials said.
   The bank said the Yugoslavian government will use the
credit to promote private-sector initiatives, seek to correct
price distortions in its economy, and "improve the allocation
and use of resources."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Referring to the country's reform efforts, it added,
"Interest rates will be set at positive levels, a market for
foreign exchange will be established and foreign-trade and
domestic pricing regimes will be liberalized."
   The bank also is expected to approve a $200 million credit
to Hungary by midyear. The International Monetary Fund
previously approved a $598 million loan to Yugoslavia and a
$206 million loan to Hungary.
   The World Bank's loan to Yugoslavia, to be repaid in 15
years, will carry a variable interest rate, currently 7.75%.
</TEXT>
