WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   IBM'S PROFIT SURGED 9.2% in the first quarter, a
surprisingly strong performance that included the company's
best U.S. results in years. The report sent IBM's stock up
$3.625, to $110.75. But some analysts cautioned that the
computer giant's outlook for all of 1990 remains uncertain.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stocks finished mixed after a blue-chip rally, triggered
by IBM's earnings report, was choked off by profit-taking and
slumping bonds. The Dow Jones industrials closed up 11.26, at
2763.06. The dollar also gained.
   ---
   Saudi Arabia urged other OPEC members to cut excess oil
production to halt the recent slide in prices. Prices rose on
U.S. futures and spot markets following the announcement.
   ---
   Four major banks posted generally weak quarterly earnings,
reflecting varying factors. Chase and Manufacturers Hanover
reported declines. Morgan and Banc One had gains.
   ---
   Bank of New England will set up a new entity to take over
much of its troubled real estate assets, industry officials
said. The plan may resemble programs formed by other banks.
   ---
   Eight publicly traded funds that were spawned by troubled
VMS Realty Partners took big charges to cover possible bad
loans, resulting in steep losses for the fourth quarter.
   ---
   Eli Lilly's profit rose 20% in the first quarter. The drug
maker plans to buy back up to $1 billion of stock and certain
convertible warrants.
   ---
   Magazine publishers are expecting an industry shakeout in
coming months due to a sharp drop in ad pages at many major
magazines.
                                                                                                       

   Time Warner is making a major effort to attract readers to
its faltering Entertainment Weekly.
   ---
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh's shareholders group agreed to back a
rival reorganization plan, marking a breakthrough in the
steelmaker's five-year bankruptcy proceedings.
   ---
   Dataproducts agreed to be acquired for $160 million by two
Hitachi affiliates, apparently ending two years of turmoil at
the firm.
   ---
   American Air withdrew a plan to boost some air fares by as
much as 23% after most other carriers failed to match the
proposed increases.
   ---
   Resorts International filed an amended Chapter 11
reorganization plan that includes selling its Paradise Island
property in the Bahamas.
   ---
   Primerica's profit jumped 62% in the first quarter,
reflecting good performances in its three main businesses.
Revenue climbed about 17%.
   ---
   The Supreme Court agreed to decide whether workers may sue
their employers under state law for allegedly firing them to
avoid having to pay pension benefits.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 142,810,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2763.06, up 11.26; transportation 1188.66, off 2.84;
utilities 213.15, up 0.37.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3321.37, off
8.34.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.78, off 0.02;
spot index 135.68, up 0.81.
   Dollar: 159.30 yen, up 1.12; 1.6775 marks, up 0.0051.
</TEXT>
