<HL>
   Business Brief -- Financial Corp. of Santa Barbara:
   Thrift Holding Firm's Loss
   Grew Sharply in 4th Period
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   FSB
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Struggling Financial Corp. of Santa Barbara posted a wider
loss for the fourth quarter of $37.9 million, or $6.28 a
share, after taking write-downs and increasing reserves
associated with new federal thrift capital requirements. In
the year earlier, the company had a loss of $9.5 million, or
$1.57 a share.
   The Santa Barbara, Calif., thrift holding concern also
disclosed that it had fired its auditor, Deloitte &amp; Touche,
over a wide range of disagreements including an auditor's
report questioning the "adequacy of the company's system of
internal controls." The auditing concern couldn't be reached
for comment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the year, Financial Corp. had a loss of $60.3 million,
or $10.01 a share, compared with a loss of $7.1 million, or
$1.24 a share, for 1988.
   Financial Corp., which is under regulatory orders
prohibiting it from making new loans, said the 1989 loss
reflected a write-down of about $12.1 million on the value of
preferred stock of a subsidiary and a write-down of $10.1
million of goodwill. The thrift said it also took reserves of
$12.3 million to cover write-downs associated with its
corporate bond portfolio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900417-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900417-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Environmental Power Corp.:
   Loss Is Reported for 1989;
   Auditors Raise Questions
</HL>
<DATE>
04/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   POWR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Environmental Power Corp., Boston, reported its second
consecutive year of big losses and said its auditors raised
questions about its ability to "continue as a going concern."
   The developer of plants that turn waste coal and trash
into electrical power reported a net loss of $4.2 million, or
55 cents a share, compared with a loss of $4.7 million, or 61
cents a share, for 1989. Revenue rose to $583,026 from
$514,341.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said the loss was partly due to $2.5 million
in reserves related to a former unit that is developing a
waste-to-energy plant in Galveston, Texas.
   Environmental Power's auditors, Ernst &amp; Young, said in
their opinion that the company's ability to continue may
depend on completing financing of its current projects on
schedule or else finding alternative financing.
   Environmental Power said it believes its "arrangements
will be sufficient," but added that there isn't any assurance
the financing will be completed on time or on favorable
terms.
</TEXT>
